description:
Japanese Honeysuckle (Lonicera japonica)

12 May 2016 
Avondale Park 
Denton, Denton County, Texas

Japanese Honeysuckle is a non-native wildflower (original to eastern Asia) that's usually manifested as a vine or bush, usually the former. For the most part it is a flowering plant that's naturalized in the Lower 48 since all but 11 states do not claim to have it and all of these are northern tier states (USDA Plants Database range map). One province in Canada also claims to have it and in all of these places of North America it is considered an introduced plant although it was introduced to North America in 1806 in Long Island, New York, that is, 210 years ago. Though not directly indicated in the sources consulted, it is surely present in Mexico as well. Because of its presence in North America, Japanese Honeysuckle is an introduced but naturalized resident of the Western Hemisphere. Avondale Park is administered by the City of Denton, Texas.

Here's the thumbnail sketch presented at the online site Invasive Plants of the U.S. for Japanese Honeysuckle: "Japanese honeysuckle is an evergreen to semi-evergreen vine that can be found either trailing or climbing to over 80 ft. (24 m) in length. Leaves are opposite, sessile, pubescent, oval and 1 to 2.5 in. (2.5-6.4 cm) long. Flowering occurs from April to July, when showy, fragrant, tubular, whitish-pink to yellow flowers develop in the axils of the leaves. Fruits develop in the fall and are small, shiny black berries. Japanese honeysuckle invades a variety of habitats including forest floors, canopies, roadsides, wetlands, and disturbed areas. Japanese honeysuckle can girdle small saplings by twining around them, and it can form dense mats in the canopies of trees, shading everything below. A native of eastern Asia, it was first introduced into North America in 1806 in Long Island, NY. Japanese honeysuckle has been planted widely throughout the United States as an ornamental, for erosion control, and for wildlife habitat."

Sources:

"Japanese Honeysuckle," Invasive Plants of the U.S., description, photographs, resources, accessed 5.12.16, http://www.invasive.org/weedcd/species/3039.htm
"Lonicera japonica Thunb. - 

Japanese honeysuckle," Plants Database, United States Department of Agriculture, Natural Resources Conservation Service, range map, photographs, description, resources, accessed 5.12.16, http://plants.usda.gov/core/profile?symbol=LOJA

description: Lonicera japonica is an evergreen, woody, twining vine. Ovate-shaped leaves are opposite, roughly 1 ½ to 3 inches long with variably pubescent petioles. The younger stems are reddish in color and are fuzzy or slightly pubescent. Hollow, older stems are hollow with brownish bark that peels in long strips. The stems are usually 80-120 feet long. Lonicera japonica has fragrant, white flowers that fade to yellow and borne in pairs on axillary peduncles. Individual flowers are tubular, with a fused two-lipped corolla.

description:
Thick honeysuckle stem, or branch? broke off at ground level under small tree shown.  This plant part of a continuous canopy of honeysuckle  approx 10m x 5m, over planted natives incl. manuka, karamu, hoheria, adjacent to regenerating native forest in Eskdale Reserve, Glenfield, Many honeysuckle-covered trees are dead, more have no leaves visible through dense multilple honeysiuckle layers of the vine, and will probably not survive. On the ground are hundreds of crisscrossing stems hidden in unmown kikuyu , blackberry and other shrub weeds. climbing adjacent trees to 4mH.  Roots with nodes up to 2cm diameter in or just above ground . This stem the thickest found so far, brittle, snapped off in several pieces this size. Weed control... [CORRECTION: annual maintenance visit is for limited selecton of species only. Currently in Eskdale Reserve this does not include honeysuckle except in wetlands.] ...by spraying of foliage with cut and paste of stems. Fat white Calystegia runners have been unearthed during removal of honeysuckle roots, and no Calystegia leaves are visible nearby, suggesting a prior invasion by Calystegia at this site is likely, and likely to recur vigorously in the absence of the honeysuckle.

description:
Seedling or shooting node, Between road and bushpath in a dense native tree planting along c.1.9km of coastal cliff and streamside, planted on completion of the 1999 road extension and bridge over Kaipatiki Estuary. 

Over the 20 years since road construction, the planting was hand-weeded for years and replanted as necessary. 
Despite ongoing weed invasion, now being attended to as budgets and volunteer time permit,  the canopy is largely intact and supports the indigenous wildlife of the area, including white-faced heron, tui, kereru, fantail, grey warbler,  ducks, occasional seabirds, and banded rail.
Now nursing spontaneously regenerating native seedlings, saplings and sporelings  throughout its length, the planting is thus meeting its intended purpose of supporting the regeneration of the naturally occurring diverse native habitats of the adjacent streamside and estuarine cliff.

description:
Suppressed by being rolled back from grass margin and karamu at top of bank, and from weeded area now in rev to left, forming  2  rolls each about a metre diameter, one up the bank and one across. Resulted in unexpectedly efficient control, containing and suppressing the entire extent of this invasion here and to the left ie in Flame Tree Bank and the adjacent Cape Honey Flower Bank (beyond which it was already controlled) since October 2018. 

Since about May 2019,  occasional visible regrowth has been tossed towards the centre of the diminishing area of  infestation, which on this bank held only a few native trees, now recovering from their involvement, and lots of wild ginger, Alocasia and tradescantia. 

By May the rolls had become sufficiently softened by rotting  to be eased back from the already-cleared areas, lifting both dying and living, but suppressed, roots of the vine as they are reached.
Viewed from the mown kikuyu margin, now holding a few mahoe, karamu and ti kouka seedlings and many exotic herb seedlings, eg Sowthistle visible here in foreground
